## ðŸ’¡ Port Mapping kya hota hai?

Docker Container ke paas **apna khud ka Network** hota hai ðŸ”’
Isliye container ke andar chal raha app **seedha bahar se access nahi hota** âŒ

To hum **bridge** banate hain jisse:

âœ” Browser (host machine se)
âœ” Container ke andar running application ko
âœ” Access kar sakta ho

Ye bridge = **Port Mapping** âœ…

---

## ðŸ” Sabse Easy Example â†’ McDonald's Stall ðŸ˜Ž

Container = McDonald's stall ðŸ”
Container ka internal counter number: **Port 80**
(burger udhar milta hai)

Par customers road par khade haiâ€¦

Road gate number: **Port 8080**

Mapping:

```
Gate 8080 (Host) â†’ Counter 80 (Container)
```

Ab koi bhi bole:
ðŸ‘‰ [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080)
âž¡ Container ke counter 80 par order chale jayega âœ…

---

## ðŸ”¥ Docker Command Example

```
docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx
```

Breakdown:

| Part     | Meaning                  |
| -------- | ------------------------ |
| -d       | Background me run        |
| -p       | Port mapping             |
| **8080** | Host Port (Aapka Laptop) |
| **80**   | Container Port           |

---

## ðŸ“Œ Host Port vs Container Port

| Host Port              | Container Port                         |
| ---------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Computer ki entry gate | Container ke andar application ka gate |
| Bahar se access hota   | Sirf container ke andar se access      |

---

## ðŸ˜Ž Why different numbers?

Kabhi host par port 80 already kisi aur app ne le rakha hota hai âŒ
To hum **custom host port** set kar sakte:

Example:

```
-p 5000:80
```

Host â†’ 5000
Container â†’ 80

Port alag
Application same âœ…

---

## âœ… Real World Use Case

| Service     | Container Port | Host Port (example) |
| ----------- | -------------- | ------------------- |
| Nginx (Web) | 80             | 8080                |
| React App   | 3000           | 3000                |
| MySQL       | 3306           | 3306                |
| Jenkins     | 8080           | 9090                |

---

## Interview Smart Answer ðŸ”¥

> **Port mapping is a mechanism that exposes containerâ€™s internal ports to the outside world.**
> Example: `-p 8080:80`
>
> Here, **8080 is host port** and **80 is container port**.
>
> It allows access to the app running inside the container.

Short, Full Marks âœ…

---

## Quick Revision in 4 Lines

* Container gate (internal) â†’ Container Port
* Laptop gate (external) â†’ Host Port
* App inside = private
* Port mapping = **public access**

